Another area of concern highlighted in the survey of over 1,000 women is the sex division ratio. According to the survey, about 55 percent of households have more male children than female. According to Article 21 of the Gabonese Constitution, all children have the right to the same names as their mothers. But because the majority of Obangalais, while staying home to take care of the children, have the power in their homes, the son is still Mr. Obangalai. This causes many of the younger women to lose their own identity.

"I have always been afraid of that possibility," says Obangalai v. "I did not want my son to have power, but only thanks to the Baluba tradition, he has a name." Godfather Dide Pascal Junge opens his Bible: "A man without understanding misleads his own soul," he recalls from one of his favorite passing gospels. Similar knowledge ("…) works to rule and lead power belongs to God, you are just an instrument. The youngest and the lowest in the family are those who should rule in the household – that is what the Bible says. "
